Their nation practises active conscription where all citizens must undergo eight weeks of basic training in either the army or navy starting at 18. Then they can choose to either serve for a year in the branch they chose or go back to civilian life, but they must still eventually serve the year in the military between the ages of 18 and 30. And if they choose to return to civilian life after their mandatory service, they will be considered a reservist until the age of 40.

by Convallaria » Sun Jan 17, 2021 9:12 pm

The large and diversified economy is mostly focused on the export of luxury and pleasure goods, including pretty much everything your avergage college student consumes, from microwave safe food products to cheap alcohol. Essentially, the sort of stuff that can't be easily massed produced in primitive economies where resources aren't as varied.

This actually makes a lot of sense, I mean when you think about it, even things like books took thousands of years and a great deal of effort to become as widespread as they are today, so it would make sense that post-apocalyptic economies would struggle to produce their own.

by Wexas » Sun Jan 17, 2021 10:13 pm

Convallaria: *crab* Los Angeles is gone *crab*

In an interesting little twist, rather than being actively and openly authoritarian and hostile towards their own citizens in the name of 'ideological unity' (I can't think of the right words for it), they guarantee the rights of their citizens freedoms of speech, religion, and even guarantee the right to an education - which while I am unsure of the full extent might include anything from 'The Government can't say someone can't get an education' to 'College is Free' - though the section on the military makes that a bit screwy. However, they are de facto allowed to subvert Declaration A through Part XIV of the constitution: Which allows the National Industrial (The national legislation) to make laws in the name of national security ala a bastardized mixture of the Patriot Act and whatever McCarthy would probably try to pass. This effectively means that groups such as Communists can be quickly subverted.

I just gotta love how sneakily subversive this is. It isn't in your face like "ha ha, you have no rights. fuck youuuuuuu" like a lot of nations would do. Rather, it's something most wouldn't even notice unless they've actually read the constitution which, given it's Chapter 14 of a multi-chapter constitution. Which, given how most OTL Americans barely know their amendments past the 10th, I highly doubt. So, I like it.

These range from the almost far-right Neo Justice Movement to the Prime Alliance Party which wants to disarm the communes - most likely leading to a centralized state. To say this nation sounds violent and unstable is understating it, though it is no surprise that these factions clash given how rapidly different their goals are.
